<TITLE> Bandarban BDR court reads out charges </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Bandarban, April 24 (bdnews24.com)  A special BDR court in Bandarban on Saturday adjourned the mutiny trial of 35 members of the 10 Rifles Battalion till October 10. The special court, set up at Baitul Ijjat BDR Training Centre in Satkania, began the proceedings for the second day at around 8:40am, with outgoing Bangladesh Rifles director general Maj Gen Moinul Islam heading the judges' panel. The 35 were accused of rebelling in support of the mutiny in Pilkhana, Dhaka on Feb 25-26. They were produced in front of the court. Lt Col Md Robiul Awal, commander of the 10 Rifles Battalion read out the charges against the BDR men. He accused said that they had broken the law and deserved punishment. The court has given the BDR men 27 days to employ lawyers or secure witnesses to defend their cases. At around 9.35am the court ordered the hearing adjourned till 9am of October 10. The special court began its hearing on April 22. This court is also set to try mutiny cases of BDR Training Centre in Satkania and Naikhyangchhari battalion of Bandarban. The bloody mutiny in Pilkhana, the BDR headquarters, saw 70 people killed, including 57 army officers deputed to the paramilitary border guards. On Nov 15 last year, the government formed six special courts, including two in Dhaka, to try about 3,500 border guards accused in 40 cases around the country. The six special courts have been trying charges of mutiny, loot and arson. Four courts in Panchgarh, Thakurgaon, Feni and Satkhira have already given their verdicts. In the event of a conviction, the maximum penalty for rebellion under the BDR Act is seven years in jail. Those accused of being involved in the Pilkhana murders will be tried separately in civilian courts. bdnews
